 <title>Roll with the Waves</title>
 <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/disabilitynation/~3/xJRlqYP8xog/roll-waves</link>
 <description>&lt;span class="inline inline-left"&gt;&lt;img src="/files/images/Sea Princess.jpg" alt="Sea Princess" title="Sea Princess"  class="image image-_original" width="492" height="150" /&gt;&lt;span class="caption" style="width: 490px;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sea Princess&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;Cruising is one of the best ways to visit new and exciting places around the world. I've been on three of them now, the most recent ended a few days ago when I returned from a Princess cruise to Alaska. The cruise was 10-days long and featured shore time in Ketchikan, Juneau and Skagway Alaska as well as a day in Victoria British Columbia. Without a doubt, Alaska is one of the most beautiful places in the world. However, for those of us with disabilities, the journey can be tricky at times.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.disabilitynation.net/blog/roll-waves"&gt;read more&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div class="feedflare"&gt;
